Topic: Choosing Right Batch Size¶

In this research, we will get intuition when choosing the batch size parameter. Batch size is very important for model training because when you decide the batch size parameter actually you decide how cost function will be. For example if you choose too big batch size your model will try to learn many samples each epoch and it mean each epoch your model take very small step. Nevertheless , this is not a bad sitution for some models but choosing too big batch size will increase the possibility of catching local minima point.

Dataset¶

Our dataset will be very simple dataset. We will use house prices dataset. Firstly, we will check the usability of dataset.

Dataset Source: https://www.kaggle.com/harlfoxem/housesalesprediction

Data Preprocessing¶

In [6]:
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler # We will use MinMaxScaler 
from numpy.random import permutation

shuffler = permutation(len(dataX))
dataX = dataX[shuffler]
dataY = dataY[shuffler]

# Shuffling the dataset

xTrain = dataX[:len(dataX) * 80 // 100] 
yTrain = dataY[:len(dataY) * 80 // 100]

xTest = dataX[len(dataX) * 80 // 100:]
yTest = dataY[len(dataY) * 80 // 100:]

# IMPORTANT NOTE : Firstly we must separate the datasets into category and then we must scale the data according to the train data

scalerX = MinMaxScaler()
scalerY = MinMaxScaler()
xTrain = scalerX.fit_transform(xTrain)
xTest = scalerX.transform(xTest)
yTrain = scalerY.fit_transform(yTrain.reshape(-1,1)).reshape(-1)
yTest = scalerY.transform(yTest.reshape(-1,1)).reshape(-1)

# We're scaling y data because we have very huge number in y data

In [ ]:
batchSizeList = [32,64,128,len(xTrain) // 30,len(xTrain) // 20 , len(xTrain) // 10 , len(xTrain)]


# Important Note: We're testing many batch_size parameter and some of them contain length of train data because we want to see 
# the effects of length of train data.

historyList = []

for index , batch_size in enumerate(batchSizeList):
    
    model = tf.keras.Sequential([
        #Dense(13 , activation = 'relu' , input_shape = xTrain.shape[1:]), # We're using relu activation to decrease linearity
        Dense(1 , input_shape = xTrain.shape[1:])
    ])
    
    #Amount of trainable variable => 14 
    #We choose very small model because we wan't to see the difference between the batch sizes and our dataset is not complicated
    
    model.compile(optimizer = 'adam' , loss = 'mse') 
    
    history = model.fit(xTrain , yTrain,
                        epochs = 200,
                        batch_size = batch_size,
                        validation_data = (xTest , yTest),
                        verbose = 2)
    
    historyList.append(history)
In [26]:
colorList = ['b-','g-','r-','c-','m-','y-','k-']

displayParameters = [5,10,50,100]

for display in displayParameters:
    for index , history in enumerate(historyList):
    
        plt.figure()
        plt.plot(history.history['loss'][display:] , colorList[index] , label = 'Batch Size => %d\nDisplay parameter %d' % (batchSizeList[index],display))
        plt.xlabel('Epochs')
        plt.ylabel('Loss')
        plt.legend()
        plt.show()

How can we understand the model can escape from local minima points ?¶

Normally, gradient descent is planned for always reduce the loss but when we choose smaller batch size than lenght of training dataset we don't execute normal gradient descent. So if our loss increase thats mean it escape from local minima point.

Result¶

We tested many parameters in this test and we got some intuition about choosing right batch_size parameter. Firstly, We saw small batch size is speeding up your training process but we must be carefull because if we chose more smaler batch size than we need we can miss global minima point and we don't want this situation. We must choose the biggest batch size which can escape from local minima points and in this test 864 ( len(xTrain) // 20 ) is the best batch size.
